Data Description¶

Data Source¶

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/maharshipandya/-spotify-tracks-dataset

Data Dictionary¶

Column Description

  • track_id: The Spotify ID for the track
  • artists: The artists' names who performed the track. If there is more than one artist, they are separated by a ;
  • album_name: The album name in which the track appears
  • track_name: Name of the track
  • popularity: The popularity of a track is a value between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular. The popularity is calculated by algorithm and is based, in the most part, on the total number of plays the track has had and how recent those plays are. Generally speaking, songs that are being played a lot now will have a higher popularity than songs that were played a lot in the past. Duplicate tracks (e.g. the same track from a single and an album) are rated independently. Artist and album popularity is derived mathematically from track popularity.
  • duration_ms: The track length in milliseconds
  • explicit: Whether or not the track has explicit lyrics (true = yes it does; false = no it does not OR unknown)
  • danceability: Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable
  • energy: Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale
  • key: The key the track is in. Integers map to pitches using standard Pitch Class notation. E.g. 0 = C, 1 = C♯/D♭, 2 = D, and so on. If no key was detected, the value is -1
  • loudness: The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB)
  • mode: Mode indicates the modality (major or minor) of a track, the type of scale from which its melodic content is derived. Major is represented by 1 and minor is 0
  • speechiness: Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. Values above 0.66 describe tracks that are probably made entirely of spoken words. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 describe tracks that may contain both music and speech, either in sections or layered, including such cases as rap music. Values below 0.33 most likely represent music and other non-speech-like tracks
  • acousticness: A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. 1.0 represents high confidence the track is acoustic
  • instrumentalness: Predicts whether a track contains no vocals. "Ooh" and "aah" sounds are treated as instrumental in this context. Rap or spoken word tracks are clearly "vocal". The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content
  • liveness: Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live. A value above 0.8 provides strong likelihood that the track is live
  • valence: A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry)
  • tempo: The overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM). In musical terminology, tempo is the speed or pace of a given piece and derives directly from the average beat duration
  • time_signature: An estimated time signature. The time signature (meter) is a notational convention to specify how many beats are in each bar (or measure). The time signature ranges from 3 to 7 indicating time signatures of 3/4, to 7/4
  • track_genre: The genre in which the track belongs

Insights¶

  • Unnamed: Row count, no analytical info, drop
  • track_id: Spotify cataloging number, no analytical info, drop
  • artists: Song performer(s), likely contributor to popularity, but nominal data type, drop
  • album_name: Album title, not likely to contribute to popularity, nominal data type, drop
  • track_name: Song title, not likely to contribute to popularity, nominal data type, drop
  • popularity: target variable
  • duration_ms: heavy right skew, most songs are between 8,000-500,000 miliseconds (8-500 seconds), but some continue to extend up to 5,237 seconds (87 min), convert to minutes for clarity
  • explicit: fairly balanced, keep as is
  • danceability: Already normalized between 0-1, keep as is
  • energy: Already normalized between 0-1, keep as is
  • key: Ordinal data 0-11 for key track is performed in, keep as is
  • loudness: Range -49.531 to 4.532, will need to normalize
  • mode: Binary if performed in major(1) or minor(0), keep as is
  • speechiness: Already normalized between 0-1, keep as is
  • acousticness: Already normalized between 0-1, keep as is
  • instrumentalness: Already normalized between 0-1, keep as is
  • liveness: Already normalized between 0-1, keep as is
  • valence: Already normalized between 0-1, keep as is
  • tempo: Beats per minute, from 0-243.372, will need to normalize
  • time_signature: measures meter from 0-5, keep as is
  • track_genre: Song genre, likely contributor to popularity, but nominal data type, drop

Cleaning the raw data steps¶

In [10]:
# Convert popularity to binary labels (1 = Popular, 0 = Not Popular)
sdata["popularity_label"] = (sdata["popularity"] > 80).astype(int)

# Normalize loudness (since values are mostly negative decibels)
sdata["loudness"] = (sdata["loudness"] - sdata["loudness"].min()) / (
    sdata["loudness"].max() - sdata["loudness"].min()
)
# Normalize tempo
sdata["tempo"] = (sdata["tempo"] - sdata["tempo"].min()) / (
    sdata["tempo"].max() - sdata["tempo"].min()
)
# Converting duration_ms to durations which is minutes & seconds for clarity
sdata["duration"] = sdata["duration_ms"] / 60000  # convert ms to minutes

# Check if 'track_id' and 'Unnamed: 0' columns exist before dropping
if 'track_id' in sdata.columns and 'Unnamed: 0' in sdata.columns:
    sdata = sdata.drop(columns=["track_id", "Unnamed: 0"])
elif 'track_id' in sdata.columns:
    sdata = sdata.drop(columns=["track_id"])
elif 'Unnamed: 0' in sdata.columns:
    sdata = sdata.drop(columns=["Unnamed: 0"])
# If neither column exists, the drop operation is skipped.

# Drop original text columns after encoding
sdata_clean = sdata.drop(columns=['artists', 'album_name', 'track_name',
              'popularity_bin', 'track_genre', 'duration_ms', 'time_signature'])
# Keeping original 'popularity' for examination of distribution and feature importance

# Remove duplicates
data_clean = sdata_clean.drop_duplicates()

# Confirm dataset cleanup
print(data_clean.info())
print(data_clean.head())

This bar chart displays the feature importance results from a RandomForestRegressor model trained on songs with popularity scores above 80.

The model identifies danceability, instrumentalness,valence and energy as the most influential features in predicting variations within this highly popular subset, suggesting that more danceable, emotionally positive tracks, with less vocals tend to receive higher popularity scores.

Other significant contributors include liveness, acousticness, and duration, indicating that tracks with subtle live elements, moderate acoustic properties, and certain length ranges also influence popularity.

These insights can inform targeted feature selection for models aimed at optimizing or predicting song popularity within the upper threshold.

Examine Feature Importance after SMOTE balancing results¶

In [ ]:
# === STEP 1: Original Train Set ===
X_orig = train_df.drop(columns=['popularity_label'])
y_orig = train_df['popularity_label']

rf_orig = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=42)
rf_orig.fit(X_orig, y_orig)

import_orig = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X_orig.columns,
    'Importance': rf_orig.feature_importances_,
    'Set': 'Original'
})

# === STEP 2: SMOTE-Balanced Train Set ===
X_bal = train_df_balanced.drop(columns=['popularity_label'])
y_bal = train_df_balanced['popularity_label']

rf_bal = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=42)
rf_bal.fit(X_bal, y_bal)

import_bal = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X_bal.columns,
    'Importance': rf_bal.feature_importances_,
    'Set': 'SMOTE'
})

# === STEP 3: Combine and Remove 'popularity' Feature ===
importances = pd.concat([import_orig, import_bal])
importances = importances[importances['Feature'] != 'popularity']  # REMOVE popularity

# Sort features by total importance across both sets
feature_order = (importances
                 .groupby('Feature')['Importance']
                 .sum()
                 .sort_values(ascending=False)
                 .index)

# === Plot ===
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
ax = sns.barplot(data=importances, x='Importance', y='Feature', hue='Set', dodge=True, order=feature_order)
plt.title('Feature Importance Comparison: Original vs SMOTE Balanced (Excl. Popularity)')
plt.xlabel('Importance Score')
plt.ylabel('Feature')
plt.legend(title='Dataset')

# Add value labels
for container in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(container, fmt="%.2f", label_type='edge', padding=2, fontsize=9)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The chart above compares feature importance scores from Random Forest classifiers trained on the original imbalanced dataset and the SMOTE-balanced version, with the popularity feature excluded to avoid target leakage.

In the original dataset, most features had very low importance, indicating that the model was likely overfitting to a small subset of the data or was biased due to class imbalance. After applying SMOTE, the importance scores became more meaningful and better distributed across several features.

Notably, features like loudness, acousticness, instrumentalness, energy, and danceability showed a significant increase in importance after balancing, suggesting that the model trained on the SMOTE dataset is leveraging a more diverse and relevant set of audio characteristics.

This demonstrates that SMOTE balancing improves model robustness by reducing overreliance on any single feature and encouraging the use of a broader, more informative feature set.

Selection of features to best predict a songs possibility of popularity¶

Based on the correlation heatmaps and feature importance rankings, the top features for predicting a song’s potential popularity are

  1. danceability: Indicates how suitable a song is for dancing; higher values often align with mainstream, upbeat tracks that tend to be more popular.

  2. energy: Reflects the intensity and activity of a track; energetic songs are typically more engaging and radio-friendly.

  3. loudness: Measures overall volume; louder songs often feel more polished or produced, which is common in popular music.

  4. speechiness: Captures the presence of spoken words; moderate values can suggest genres like rap or pop that resonate with broad audiences.

  5. acousticness: Represents the likelihood a song is acoustic; lower values are common in modern, heavily produced hits, making it useful for distinguishing popular from niche acoustic tracks.

These features consistently show strong importance scores and moderate positive correlations with high popularity. danceability and energy are directly linked to how rhythmically engaging and intense a track feels, while loudness and speechiness may reflect vocal presence and production style.

acousticness, though slightly negatively correlated, adds complementary contrast in genre differentiation, helping models generalize across song types.

This KDE plot visualizes predicted probabilities from the DNN model. Class 0 (Not Popular) is shown in blue and Class 1 (Popular) in red. DNN models output continuous probability scores, enabling this density comparison. If comparing to a Decision Tree, the distribution would be sharply split at 0 and 1, with no smooth curves.

In [61]:
# Manual training loop
for opt_name, opt in optimizers.items():
    for neurons in neurons_list:
        for batch_size in batch_sizes:
            for epochs in epochs_list:
                print(f"\n Training: optimizer={opt_name}, neurons={neurons}, batch_size={batch_size}, epochs={epochs}")

                model = Sequential([
                    Dense(neurons, input_dim=X_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu'),
                    Dense(neurons // 2, activation='relu'),
                    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid') # Changed the output layer to a single neuron with sigmoid activation
                ])
                model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

                # Train the model
                history = model.fit(
                    X_train_scaled, y_train,
                    batch_size=batch_size,
                    epochs=epochs,
                    validation_split=0.2,
                    verbose=0
                )

                # Evaluate on test set
                y_pred = (model.predict(X_test_scaled, verbose=0) > 0.5).astype(int) # Predict probabilities and convert to binary labels
                acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
                print(f"Accuracy: {acc:.4f}")

                # Save best model
                if acc > best_acc:
                    best_acc = acc
                    best_model = model
                    best_params = {
                        "optimizer": opt_name,
                        "neurons": neurons,
                        "batch_size": batch_size,
                        "epochs": epochs
                    }

print("\n Tuning complete")
print(f" Total time: {time.time() - start_time:.2f}s")
print(f" Best Accuracy: {best_acc:.4f}")
print(f" Best Params: {best_params}")

In [48]:
# Step 4: Manual tuning loop
for act in activations:
    for drop in dropout_rates:
        for neurons in neurons_list:
            for batch_size in batch_sizes:
                for epochs in epochs_list:
                    for lr in learning_rates:
                        for opt_name in optimizer_names:
                            print(f"\nTraining: activation={act}, dropout={drop}, neurons={neurons}, bs={batch_size}, epochs={epochs}, lr={lr}, opt={opt_name}")
                            loop_start = time.time()

                            # Select optimizer
                            if opt_name == 'adam':
                                optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=lr)
                            elif opt_name == 'sgd':
                                optimizer = SGD(learning_rate=lr)

                            # Clear TensorFlow session
                            K.clear_session()

                            # Build model
                            model = Sequential()
                            model.add(Dense(neurons, input_dim=X_train_small.shape[1], activation=act))
                            if drop > 0:
                                model.add(Dropout(drop))
                            model.add(Dense(neurons // 2, activation=act))
                            model.add(Dense(len(np.unique(y)), activation='sigmoid'))

                            model.compile(
                                optimizer=optimizer,
                                loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                                metrics=['accuracy']
                            )

                            # Add early stopping
                            early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=2, restore_best_weights=True)

                            # Train
                            history = model.fit(
                                X_train_small, y_train_small,
                                batch_size=batch_size,
                                epochs=epochs,
                                validation_split=0.2,
                                verbose=0,
                                callbacks=[early_stop]
                            )

                            # Evaluate
                            y_pred = np.argmax(model.predict(X_test_scaled, verbose=0), axis=1)
                            acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
                            print(f"→ Accuracy: {acc:.4f}")
                            print(f"Time: {time.time() - loop_start:.2f}s")

                            # Save best
                            if acc > best_acc:
                                best_acc = acc
                                best_model = model
                                best_params = {
                                    "activation": act,
                                    "dropout": drop,
                                    "neurons": neurons,
                                    "batch_size": batch_size,
                                    "epochs": epochs,
                                    "learning_rate": lr,
                                    "optimizer": opt_name
                                }

# Step 5: Final result
print("\n Tuning complete")
print(f"Total time: {time.time() - start_time:.2f}s")
print(f" Best Accuracy: {best_acc:.4f}")
print(f" Best Params: {best_params}")

# Add value labels on bars
def add_labels(bars):
    for bar in bars:
        height = bar.get_height()
        ax.annotate(f'{height:.2f}', xy=(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, height),
                    xytext=(0, 3), textcoords="offset points", ha='center', va='bottom')

add_labels(bars3)
